1) Code Smells & Design Pattern Fix
// ❌ BAD
public void send(Notification n) {
    if (n.getChannel().equals("EMAIL")) { sendEmail(n); }
    else if (n.getChannel().equals("SMS")) { sendSMS(n); }
    else if (n.getChannel().equals("PUSH")) { sendPush(n); }
}

smell:
1) if-else chain on type/channel: Open/Closed Principle — adding new channel = modify existing code
2) Magic strings "EMAIL", "SMS": Typo-prone, no compile-time safety
3) Single class owns all send logic: Single Responsibility Principle
4) Not extensible: Adding WHATSAPP requires touching this method
5) No null check on getChannel(): NPE risk

Recommended Design — Strategy + Factory Pattern
Step 1 — Replace Magic Strings with Enum
public enum NotificationChannel {
    EMAIL, SMS, PUSH, WHATSAPP  // ✅ compile-time safe, extensible
}

Step 2 — Strategy Interface
java// Strategy contract — each channel implements this
public interface NotificationSender {
    void send(Notification notification);
    NotificationChannel supportedChannel();
}

Step 3 — Concrete Strategies (One per channel)
java@Component
public class EmailNotificationSender implements NotificationSender {

    @Override
    public void send(Notification notification) {
        log.info("Sending EMAIL to {}", notification.getRecipient());
        // SMTP / SES logic here
    }

    @Override
    public NotificationChannel supportedChannel() {
        return NotificationChannel.EMAIL;
    }
}

@Component
public class SmsNotificationSender implements NotificationSender {

    @Override
    public void send(Notification notification) {
        log.info("Sending SMS to {}", notification.getRecipient());
        // Twilio / SNS logic here
    }

    @Override
    public NotificationChannel supportedChannel() {
        return NotificationChannel.SMS;
    }
}

@Component
public class PushNotificationSender implements NotificationSender {

    @Override
    public void send(Notification notification) {
        log.info("Sending PUSH to {}", notification.getRecipient());
        // FCM / APNs logic here
    }

    @Override
    public NotificationChannel supportedChannel() {
        return NotificationChannel.PUSH;
    }
}

Step 4 — Factory to resolve Strategy
java@Component
public class NotificationSenderFactory {

    private final Map<NotificationChannel, NotificationSender> senderMap;

    // ✅ Spring auto-injects all NotificationSender implementations
    public NotificationSenderFactory(List<NotificationSender> senders) {
        this.senderMap = senders.stream()
                .collect(Collectors.toMap(
                        NotificationSender::supportedChannel,
                        Function.identity()
                ));
    }

    public NotificationSender resolve(NotificationChannel channel) {
        return Optional.ofNullable(senderMap.get(channel))
                .orElseThrow(() -> new UnsupportedOperationException(
                        "No sender registered for channel: " + channel));
    }
}

Step 5 — Clean NotificationService (Zero if-else)
java@Service
@Slf4j
public class NotificationService {

    private final NotificationSenderFactory senderFactory;

    public NotificationService(NotificationSenderFactory senderFactory) {
        this.senderFactory = senderFactory;
    }

    // ✅ No if-else — fully closed for modification, open for extension
    public void send(Notification notification) {
        Assert.notNull(notification, "Notification must not be null");
        Assert.notNull(notification.getChannel(), "Channel must not be null");

        senderFactory
                .resolve(notification.getChannel())
                .send(notification);
    }
}

Adding a New Channel — Zero existing code changes
java// ✅ Just add new class — nothing else touched
@Component
public class WhatsAppNotificationSender implements NotificationSender {

    @Override
    public void send(Notification notification) {
        log.info("Sending WHATSAPP to {}", notification.getRecipient());
        // WhatsApp Business API logic
    }

    @Override
    public NotificationChannel supportedChannel() {
        return NotificationChannel.WHATSAPP;
    }
}

Spring auto-discovers it, factory auto-registers it. Zero changes to existing code.

Followup question:

=================
How encryption for sensitive data (like mobile numbers) within above design ?
=================
To integrate encryption for sensitive data (like mobile numbers) within your existing Strategy and Factory architecture,
you should focus on Separation of Concerns. You don't want your encryption logic scattered across every NotificationSender.

Here is the recommended design using the Decorator Pattern and the Proxy Pattern concepts.

The Decorator Pattern is perfect here.
-------------------------------------
It allows you to wrap your existing SmsNotificationSender with a "Logging Decorator" that handles the encryption/masking logic before the actual sending happens.
This keeps your business logic (sending) separate from your security logic (encryption).

Single Responsibility: The SmsNotificationSender only cares about Twilio/SNS.
The Decorator only cares about PII (Personally Identifiable Information) security.

Transparency: The NotificationService doesn't even know the data is being encrypted for logs; it just calls .send().

Implementation Steps:
Step 1: Create an Encryption Utility
First, define a service to handle the heavy lifting.
In a production environment, this would interface with AWS KMS, Azure Key Vault, or HashiCorp Vault.

@Service
public class EncryptionService {
    // In reality, use a library like AES-256 or a Vault provider
    public String encrypt(String plainText) {
        return Base64.getEncoder().encodeToString(plainText.getBytes());
    }
}

Step 2: Create the Logging Decorator
Instead of modifying SmsNotificationSender.java, create a decorator.
Note the @Primary or @Qualifier usage to ensure Spring knows which one to use.

@Component
@Primary // Tells the Factory to pick this over the raw implementation
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class SecureSmsNotificationSender implements NotificationSender {

    private final SmsNotificationSender originalSender; // The real sender
    private final EncryptionService encryptionService;

    @Override
    public void send(Notification notification) {
        // 1. Secure the data for logging
        String rawMobile = notification.getRecipient();
        String encryptedMobile = encryptionService.encrypt(rawMobile);

        log.info("Sending SMS to encrypted recipient: {}", encryptedMobile);

        // 2. Delegate to the actual sender for the real API call
        originalSender.send(notification);
    }

    @Override
    public NotificationChannel supportedChannel() {
        return NotificationChannel.SMS;
    }
}


Alternative: Aspect-Oriented Programming (AOP)
---------------------------------------------
f you want to apply encryption across multiple channels (SMS, WhatsApp, etc.) without writing multiple decorators, use AOP (Proxy Pattern).
This is the "cleanest" way to handle cross-cutting concerns like logging and security.

Step 1: Create a Custom Annotation
@Target(ElementType.METHOD)
@Retention(RetentionPolicy.RUNTIME)
public @interface SecureLog { }

Step 2: Create the Aspect
@Aspect
@Component
public class LoggingAspect {

    @Autowired
    private EncryptionService encryptionService;

    @Before("@annotation(SecureLog) && args(notification)")
    public void encryptLog(Notification notification) {
        String encrypted = encryptionService.encrypt(notification.getRecipient());
        log.info("Secure Transaction Initiated for: {}", encrypted);
    }
}

Step 3: Apply to Strategies
@Override
@SecureLog // Just drop this on any method you want to protect
public void send(Notification notification) {
    // Logic...
}


